04483nam a22007455i 9780231538909DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014029304  a(OCoLC)905914035  a97802315389097 a10.7312/reme169622doi  a(DE-B1597)458475  a(OCoLC)904237992  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1995.9.E96bR395 2015 4aPN1995.9.E96bR395 2015 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/6112231 aRemes, Justin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMotion(less) Pictures :bThe Cinema of Stasis /cJustin Remes. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b‹B›10 b&w photographs‹/B›  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Serious Immobilities -- t3. Stasis in Fluxus -- t4. Boundless Ontologies -- t5. Colored Blindness -- t6. Conclusion -- tAppendix 1. The Cinema of Stasis -- tAppendix 2. Films Relevant to Understanding the Cinema of Stasis -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConducting the first comprehensive study of films that do not move, Justin Remes challenges the primacy of motion in cinema and tests the theoretical limits of film aesthetics and representation. Reading experimental films such as Andy Warhol's Empire (1964), the Fluxus work Disappearing Music for Face (1965), Michael Snow's So Is This (1982), and Derek Jarman's Blue (1993), he shows how motionless films defiantly showcase the static while collapsing the boundaries between cinema, photography, painting, and literature. Analyzing four categories of static film--furniture films, designed to be viewed partially or distractedly; protracted films, which use extremely slow motion to impress stasis; textual films, which foreground the static display of letters and written words; and monochrome films, which display a field of monochrome color as their image--Remes maps the interrelations between movement, stillness, and duration and their complication of cinema's conventional function and effects. Arguing all films unfold in time, he suggests duration is more fundamental to cinema than motion, initiating fresh inquiries into film's manipulation of temporality, from rigidly structured works to those with more ambiguous and open-ended frameworks. Remes's discussion integrates the writings of Roland Barthes, Gilles Deleuze, Tom Gunning, Rudolf Arnheim, Raymond Bellour, and Noel Carroll and will appeal to students of film theory, experimental cinema, intermedia studies, and aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics). 0aExperimental filmsxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/reme1696240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231538909.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK